On 9/28/07, Stephen Smith &lt;steve@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;   Hi,
&gt;
&gt; I consider myself more of a mockist TDD practitioner than a classicist
&gt; these days - I would strongly advocate mocking to
&gt; keep your tests fast and simple. Why test a third party application such
&gt; as Hibernate? That&#39;s not your job, surely?
&gt;
&gt; If you want to test your classes which use Hibernate, mock the actual
&gt; Hibernate classes within your code and write some
&gt; behaviour driven tests, e.g. &quot;my fetch method calls Hibernate with this
&gt; HQL&quot;. That way you ensure you&#39;re using Hibernate
&gt; in the right way.
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;d also advocate writing tests against your Hibernate config... test
&gt; _how_ you use a third party application like
&gt; Spring or Hibernate, but not the third party application itself.
&gt;
&gt; S
&gt;
